\frametitle{Loss function}

Let $L(\theta,\delta(y))$ for an unknown quantity $\theta$ and a decision $\delta(y)$ based on the data $y$. \pause 

\end{frame}


\begin{frame}
\frametitle{How many quarters in the jar?}

Suppose a jar is filled up to a pre-specified line. \pause
Let $\theta_0$ be the number of quarters in the jar. \pause
Provide a probability distribution for your uncertainty in $\theta$. \pause
Suppose you choose 
\[ 
\theta \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)
\]
even though 
\begin{itemize}
\item $\theta$ must be positive \pause and
\item $\theta$ is an integer. 
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}


\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Guessing how many quarters are in the jar.}

Now you are asked to guess how many quarters are in the jar. \pause
What should you guess? 

\vspace{0.2in} \pause

Approximately (ignoring the continuous density for $\theta$), 
your utility is $\theta$ if $\theta=\theta_0$. \pause
The expected utility, i.e. risk, is 
\[
E[U(\theta)] = \int \theta p(\theta) d\theta = \int \theta \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma} e^{-(\theta-\mu)^2/2\sigma^2}.
\]

\vspace{0.2in} \pause

The optimal decision is the one that maximizes expected utility, i.e. 
\[
\sup_\theta E[U(\theta)]
\]

\end{frame}



