\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Guessing how many quarters are in the jar.}

Now you are asked to guess how many quarters are in the jar. \pause
What should you guess? 

\vspace{0.2in} \pause

If the truth is $\theta_0$, then your return (utility) for a guess $\theta$ is 
\[ 
U(\theta,\theta_0) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\theta & \mbox{if }\theta=\theta_0 \\
0 & \mbox{if }\theta\ne\theta_0 
\end{array} \right.
\]

\vspace{0.2in} \pause

The optimal guess is the one that maximizes your expected return. \pause
If you guess $y$, then your expected return (ignoring discreteness) is 
\[ 
E_\theta[U(\theta,\theta_0)] = \int U(\theta,\theta_0) p(y) dy = \int y p(y) dy = \int y \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma} e^{-(y-\mu)^2/2\sigma^2}.
